1) Define a Java class person with private instance variables name and age. Provide four
constructors in the class, one with no arguments, second with name only as an argument,
third with age only as argument fourth with name & age as argument.

Code:

class Person {
    private String name;
    private int age;
    Person() {
        System.out.println("Default/non-parameterized constructor");
    }
    Person(String name) {
        System.out.println("only name as arg");
        this.name = name;
    }
    Person(int age) {
        System.out.println("only age as arg");
        this.age = age;
    }
    Person(String name,int age) {
        System.out.println("name and age as args");
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Person p1 = new Person();
        Person p2 = new Person(43);
        Person p3 = new Person("Jack");
        Person p4 = new Person("Jack",43);
        Person p5 = new Person(45);
    }
}

2) Define a class Employee with private instance variables empid, name and
salary. Create a static variable to store an integer value(initially 0),
which gets incremented on instantiation, this value can be use to generate emptied
so that every employee has autogenerated unique empid. Define a private method
to generate empid. Provide two constructors in the class, one is taking two arguments
(name and salary) and the other one is non parameterized. Non parameterized constructor
ask name and salary from the user.

Code:

public class Employee {
    private int empId;
    private String name;
    private float salary;
    static int var;
    Employee() {
        ++var;
        java.util.Scanner sr = new java.util.Scanner(System.in);
        this.generateEmpId();
        System.out.println("Enter name :");
        name = sr.next();
        System.out.println("Enter salary :");
        salary = sr.nextFloat();
    }
    Employee(String name, int salary) {
        ++var;
        this.generateEmpId();
        this.name = name;
        this.salary = salary;
    }
    private void generateEmpId() {
        this.empId = var;
    }
    void displayEmpDetails() {
        System.out.println("Employee ID : "+empId);
        System.out.println("Name        : "+name);
        System.out.println("Salary      : "+salary);
    }
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Employee e1 = new Employee();
        Employee e2 = new Employee("Jack",4300000);
        e1.displayEmpDetails();
        e2.displayEmpDetails();
    }
}

3) Define a class Box with private instance variables length, breadth and height.
Provide three constructors in the class, first with no argument, second with one argument
and third with three arguments.

Code:

public class Box {
    private int length, breadth, height;
    Box(){

    }
    {
        length = 10;
        breadth = 14;
        height = 12;
    }
    Box(int length){
        this.length = length;
    }
    Box(int length, int breadth, int height){
        this.length = length;
        this.breadth = breadth;
        this.height = height;
    }
    void showDimensions(){
        System.out.println("Length: "+length);
        System.out.println("Breadth: "+breadth);
        System.out.println("Height: "+height);
    }
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Box b1 = new Box();
        Box b2 = new Box(45);
        Box b3 = new Box(40,100,50);
        b1.showDimensions();
        b2.showDimensions();
        b3.showDimensions();
    }
}

4) Define a class Time with private instance variables hr, min and sec. Provide three
 constructors in the class, first one takes no argument, second takes one argument as seconds
 and third takes three arguments for hour min and seconds.
 
Code:

public class Time {
    private int hr, min, sec;
    {
        hr = 0;
        min = 0;
        sec = 0;
    }
    Time(){

    }
    Time(int sec){
        this.sec = sec;
    }
    Time(int sec, int min, int hr){
        this.sec = sec;
        this.min = min;
        this.hr = hr;
    }
    void showTime() {
        System.out.println(this.hr+" hours "+this.min+" minutes "+this.sec+" seconds ");
    }
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Time t1 = new Time();
        Time t2 = new Time(30);
        Time t3 = new Time(45,23,2);
        t1.showTime();
        t2.showTime();
        t3.showTime();
    }
}

5) Define a class Customer with instance variables id, name, mobile and email.
Provide constructors to initialize members variables of Customer. Define first
constructor with four arguments, and second constructor with three arguments
leaving argument for email.

Code:

package constructors;

public class Customer {
    int id;
    String name;
    long mobileNo;
    String email;
    static int var;
    {
        this.id = ++var;
    }
    Customer(int id, String name, long mobileNo, String email){
        this.id = id;
        this.name = name;
        this.mobileNo = mobileNo;
        this.email = email;
    }
    Customer(int id, String name, long mobileNo){
        this.id = id;
        this.name = name;
        this.mobileNo = mobileNo;
    }
    Customer(){

    }
    void ShowCustomerDetails(){
        System.out.println("\nCustomer Id: "+this.id);
        System.out.println("Customer Name: "+this.name);
        System.out.println("Customer mobile number: "+this.mobileNo);
        System.out.println("Customer Email: "+this.email);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Customer c1 = new Customer();
        Customer c2 = new Customer(2,"Faizan",9568494023L, "faizan@gmail.com");
        Customer c3 = new Customer(3,"Labiba",9560427851L);
        Customer c4 = new Customer();
        Customer c5 = new Customer();
        c1.ShowCustomerDetails();
        c2.ShowCustomerDetails();
        c3.ShowCustomerDetails();
        c4.ShowCustomerDetails();
        c5.ShowCustomerDetails();
    }
}
